{{UDP|date=January 2018}} {{notability|Companies|date=July 2017}} {{Orphan|date=February 2013}}
{{Lowercase title}} {{Infobox company | name = Dealchecker | owner = Easyvoyage Group | foundation = 2005 | founder = Alex Saint, Troy Collins and Andrew Bredon | location_city = [[London]] | location_country = [[United Kingdom]] | homepage = [http://www.dealchecker.co.uk/ www.dealchecker.co.uk] | num_employees = 25 }} '''dealchecker''' is a UK-based travel comparison website. The site does not sell any flights or holidays but provides users with a variety of search tools which enables them to compare prices between competing travel companies. dealchecker initially launched as a flight search engine, working on a [[pay-per-click]] (PPC) model with its partners. New search tools were added in subsequent years including hotel search in 2008 and cruise search in 2012.<ref>[http://www.breakingtravelnews.com/news/article/new-cruise-pages-for-dealchecker.co.uk New cruise pages for dealchecker.co.uk | News | Breaking Travel News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In addition to online search tools, dealchecker publishes a weekly [[newsletter]] highlighting 20 travel deals, which are all vetted by researchers at dealchecker.
==History== dealchecker is the first website developed by DMC digital. dealchecker experienced early success in the years following its launch – particularly in July 2007, when the site achieved a 102% increase in web traffic <ref>[http://hotelmarketing.com/index.php/content/article/dealchecker.co.uk_experiences_summer_surge Dealchecker.co.uk experiences summer surge<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and was awarded second place in the Best Travel Website category at the 2007 Telegraph Travel Awards.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/738947/Telegraph-Travel-Awards-results-in-full.html Telegraph Travel Awards: results in full - Telegraph<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In November 2010, dealchecker launched a new, luxury travel club, Secret Escapes.<ref>[https://techcrunch.com/2011/10/18/secret-escapes-attracts-new-funding-and-a-battle-hardened-ceo-2/ Secret Escapes attracts new funding and a battle-hardened CEO | TechCrunch<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The company was purchased in 2011 by French online travel publishers EasyVoyage.<ref>[http://www.tnooz.com/2011/02/03/news/easyvoyage-buys-dealchecker-traveljungle-and-fsi-travel-for-euro-10m EasyVoyage buys Dealchecker, TravelJungle and FSI Travel for Euro 10M | Tnooz<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> This prompted a change in management as Saint and Collins left to develop [[Secret Escapes]]. Mark Attwell joined dealchecker as managing director from his previous position as e-commerce chief at [[comparethemarket.com]] <ref>[http://www.travolution.co.uk/articles/2011/09/16/5021/dealchecker-poaches-comparethemarket-com-e-commerce-chief.html Dealchecker poaches Comparethemarket.com e-commerce chief - Travolution.co.uk<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
