[[File:William Richard Morfill Rothenstein.jpg|thumb|William Morfill, 1894 drawing by [[William Rothenstein]]]]
'''William Richard Morfill''' [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]] (17 November 1834&nbsp;– 9 November 1909) was Professor of Russian and the other Slavonic languages at the [[University of Oxford]] from 1900 until his death. He was the first professor of Russian in Britain,<ref name="Mail" /> and his house in [[North Oxford]] was marked with a commemorative [[blue plaque]] by the [[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board]] in 2009.<ref name="plaque">[http://www.oxfordshireblueplaques.org.uk/plaques/morfill.html William Richard Morfill (1834–1909)], [[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Scheme]], UK.</ref>

==Life==
William Richard Morfill, the second child and first son of a professional musician called William Morfill from [[Maidstone]], Kent, was born on 17 November 1834. After studying at [[Maidstone Grammar School]] and [[Tonbridge School]], he [[matriculation|matriculated]] at the [[University of Oxford]] as a member of [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford|Corpus Christi College]], on 28 May 1853. He moved to [[Oriel College, Oxford|Oriel College]] with a scholarship in classics later in 1853.  He obtained his BA degree in 1857, although this was only a pass degree as he had fallen seriously ill during the examinations. He remained in [[Oxford]] after graduation, giving private tuition.<ref name=ODNB/> His [[MA (Oxon)|Oxford MA]] was awarded in 1860, the same year in which he married Charlotte Lee and in which his first published translations from Russian appeared.<ref name=ODNB/><ref>{{cite book|last=Foster|first=Joseph|authorlink=Joseph Foster (genealogist)|title=Alumni Oxonienses: The Members of the University of Oxford, 1715–1886|isbn=978-1-85506-843-8 |year=1891–92|page=978|url=https://archive.org/stream/alumnioxoniense01oxfogoog#page/n203/mode/2up}}</ref>

Between 1865 and 1869, he lectured in philosophy and modern history at one of the private halls attached to the university, [[Charsley's Hall]].<ref name=ODNB>{{cite web|first=Gerald |last=Stone|title=Morfill, William Richard (1834–1909)|work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=October 2009 |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/35099|accessdate=5 August 2010}} {{ODNBsub}}</ref>

Morfill had had an interest in foreign languages since school days, encouraged by a Tonbridge teacher who gave him a Russian grammar.  He first visited Russia in 1870 and [[Prague]] in 1871, learning languages as he travelled; a visit to [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] in 1888 led to an article on Georgian literature. His interest in [[Slavonic language]]s was rewarded with his appointment in 1870 by Oxford to provide the first lectures of the Ilchester Foundation, endowed to encourage studies in this area. He gave further lectures in this series in 1873 and 1883, leading to his 1883 publication ''Dawn of European Literature: Slavonic Literature''. By this stage, his wife had died (in 1881; there were no children) and he took comfort in his work. He was appointed [[Reader (academic rank)|Reader]] in Russian and the other Slavonic languages in 1889 and Professor in 1900. Russian was not a degree subject at Oxford until 1904: it has been said that Oxford's "approval of the languages he had cultivated while they lay outside the curriculum is Morfill's most enduring achievement."<ref name=ODNB/>

He was the first professor of Russian in Britain.<ref name=Mail>{{cite news|url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/pagepeel/4703253.Blue_plaque_honours_Britain_s_first_professor_of_Russian/|title=Blue plaque honours Britain's first professor of Russian |work=[[Oxford Mail]]|date=26 October 2009|accessdate=5 August 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> He also became Curator of the [[Taylor Institution]] and was appointed a [[Fellow of the British Academy]] in 1903.<ref name=Who/> He was awarded an honorary doctorate by [[Charles University]], Prague in 1908.<ref name=ODNB/> His publications included ''Slavonic Literature'' (1883), ''A history of Russia from the birth of Peter the Great to the death of Alexander II'' (1902) and various books on grammar in Polish, Serbian, Bulgarian and Russian, as well as translations.<ref name=Who>{{cite web|title=Morfill, William Richard|work=Who Was Who 1920–2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|date=December 2007 |url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U189158|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref> He died on 9 November 1909 and was buried in the same grave as his wife.<ref name=ODNB/>
[[File:William Morfill blue plaque, Park Town, Oxford.jpg|thumb|William Richard Morfill, commemorative plaque in Park Town, Oxford]]
In 2009, the [[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board]] marked 42 [[Park Town, Oxford|Park Town]], where Morfill lived from 1863 to 1899, with a plaque to commemorate him.<ref name="plaque" /> The Board's secretary said that the house had been like a "cultural embassy", where people came to learn languages, and that Morfill had been chosen for being a "great pioneer" who had spent his life establishing Russian and Slavonic languages in Oxford.<ref name=Mail/>

